from <i>moretón</i> ‘brown, tanned’ (of skin).","French: nickname from a double diminutive of   More   2 ‘Moor’. Compare   Moret  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Morton","meanings":["English and Scottish: habitational name from any of the many places called Mor(e)ton, named with Old English <i>mōr</i> ‘moor’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’. There has probably been some confusion with   Morten  , and perhaps also with   Murton  . This English name has also been established in Ireland since the 13th century.","American shortened and altered form of Swedish <b>Mårtensson</b> or <b>Mortensson</b> (see   Martenson   and   Mortenson  ), which could also be substituted for the Finnish cognate <b>Marttinen</b>.","French: shortened form of   Moreton   3."]}]},{"name":"of","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Chinese Young, Sung, Jung, Yong, Chang, Kwang, Sang, Dong, Hyun, Jae, Jin, Kyung, Jong, Chong, Chung, Byung, Jeong, Pyong, Myong, Hak, Jin Hwan, Sook, Yeong, Choon.","Korean: variant of   O  .","Japanese: variant of <b>Ō</b> (see   O  )."],"variants":[{"name":"O","meanings":["(1997: 122;2010: NA)","Some characteristic forenames:  Chinese Young, Bo Young, Chae, Chong Hwan, Dong Kun, Ho, Hwan, Hyun, Jong, Jung, Ki Soon, Kwang.  Korean Min, Chong, Chol, Jung Ho, Myong, Sa, Sung Kyun.","Korean (오; Chinese character: 吳): historically, there were two Chinese characters for the O surname, but by the late Koryŏ period (14th century  AD ), one of them had disappeared. Some records indicate that there are as many as 210 different clans for the remaining character, but only sixteen can be positively documented. All sixteen of these clans originate from the same ancestor, O Ch’ŏm (吳 瞻), who migrated to Korea from China during the reign of Shilla's King Chijŭng (500–514  AD ). <i>O</i> is a common surname throughout Korea. Compare   Oh  ."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]},{"name":"Mary","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From Latin <i>Maria</i> via Old Welsh <i>Meir</i>.  See  <b>Mary</b> ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Margaret Mary Moreton of Haughton-Fowke was born in 1530, in Haughton, Shropshire, England, United Kingdom as the daughter of John Moreton and Mary. She had at least 1 daughter with Roger Bradshaw Fowke, 5th Lord Brewood. She died in 1559, in Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 29."},"et":{"1530–1559":"1530–1559","1525–1576":"1525–1576","1556–1590":"1556–1590","1500–1560":"1500–1560","–Female":"Surnud","1525":"1525","1556":"1556","1500":"1500","1576":"1576","1530":"1530","1560":"1560","1590":"1590","1559":"1559","Haughton, Shropshire, England":"Haughton, Shropshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Brewood, Staffordshire, Kingdom of England":"Brewood, Staffordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Gunston Hall, Staffordshire, England":"Staffordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1530–1559":"1530–1559","1525–1576":"1525–1576","1556–1590":"1556–1590","1500–1560":"1500–1560","–Female":"Kuollut","1525":"1525","1556":"1556","1500":"1500","1576":"1576","1530":"1530","1560":"1560","1590":"1590","1559":"1559","Haughton, Shropshire, England":"Haughton, Shropshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Brewood, Staffordshire, Kingdom of England":"Brewood, Staffordshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Gunston Hall, Staffordshire, England":"Staffordshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1530–1559":"1530–1559","1525–1576":"1525–1576","1556–1590":"1556–1590","1500–1560":"1500–1560","–Female":"Décédée","1525":"1525","1556":"1556","1500":"1500","157